 inventories without any 3rd party extensions!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The salable quantity is stored in view.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2. Understanding the workflow of order placement &amp; changes in Magento salable quantity and quantity:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/tjsmy9QALsg\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"align\":\"center\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed aligncenter is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/tjsmy9QALsg\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When a customer places an order, the salable quantity is reduced. Note that, the quantity is not decreased even when the order is placed.<br>Now when the admin creates the shipment for the order from the backend, we can see that the quantity is reduced as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Any doubts about salable quantity and quantity in Magento 2? If so, please mention them in the Comments section below.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also, do share the solution with the Magento community via social media.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Magento 2 Salable Quantity vs Quantity – Know the Difference','The concept of salable quantity came into existence with the Magento 2 MSI and this post explains the difference between Magento 2 salable quantity and quantity.','inherit','closed','closed','','67-revision-v1','','','2023-02-09 21:17:23','2023-02-09 14:17:23','',67,'https://sharing.knowledge/?p=70',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2023-02-09 21:34:33','2023-02-09 14:34:33','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Will ChatGPT replace programmers? Here’s what experts think about it. 💡</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://openai.com/blog/chatgpt/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">OpenAI’s ChatGPT</a> is a hot topic amongst internet users these days; the reason is simple:<strong> it can do almost anything! 😉</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It had a record-breaking launch success with over 1 million+ registrations within a week of its release!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>ChatGPT is a large language model trained on a massive amount of textual data, which is ridiculously good at understanding user prompts and responding. The AI-based chatbot is surprising people with its <strong>insane capabilities</strong>. It can write articles, prepare emails, perform basic SEO tasks, solve maths problems, write programs in different programming languages, and find problems in existing code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This makes it a clever AI assistant for various day-to-day tasks for the professionals, such as programmers. But, on the dark side, many people consider it a threat to their occupations. One of the hottest topics of these days on social media &amp; online forums is <strong><em>Can ChatGPT replace developers?</em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We reached out to seven experts to share their views on whether OpenAI’s ChatGPT is a replacement for human developers/programmers or not. Here is what the experts think:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>7 Experts Share Their Views on — Is ChatGPT Going to Replace Developers?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:table {\"align\":\"center\",\"backgroundColor\":\"white\",\"className\":\"is-style-regular\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table aligncenter is-style-regular\"><table class=\"has-white-background-color has-background\"><tbody><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-72\" style=\"width: 500px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-6.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“Skilled Developers No Need to Worry About ChatGPT” – Sanjay Jethva, CEO at Meetanshi</strong><br><br>“Human developers will always be required to complete a development process, no matter what.<br>ChatGPT may be quick, efficient, and error-proof when it comes to developing short code snippets. But, if we zoom out, it lacks the required creative problem-solving approach, which is a must to build a solution framework. The AI-based tool may help you build the code blocks faster, but you’ll definitely require a skilled developer to connect those blocks in an organized way to get the desired results.<br>Thus, ChatGPT or any other AI tool is not going to replace human developers; but can significantly increase their overall productivity.<br>With that in mind, it is surely going to reduce the development workforce required to build solutions that may affect junior-level or less-skilled development professionals. However, the jobs of high-level development professionals are going to be more valuable than ever.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-74\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-7.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“ChatGPT is Additional Asset to Developers; Not a Replacement” – Lucjan Suski, CEO and Co-Founder of Surfer</strong>.<br><br>“ChatGPT or Natural Language Processing (NLP) technology will not be able to replace developers anytime soon due to its lack of flexibility across different programming languages. NLP can assist developers by automating mundane tasks such as code refactoring but cannot completely replace them because no machine can match the innovation &amp; creativity brought by an experienced programmer when problem-solving. Moreover, developing software requires debugging which machines are still not capable enough for at present time.<br>In conclusion, developers are here to stay for a long time and ChatGPT or NLP will be used as an additional asset to accelerate the development process.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-75\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-8.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“ChatGPT Can’t Handle Complex Tasks” – Rajesh Namase, Co-Founder and Tech Blogger at TechRT.</strong><br><br>“ChatGPT may have some advantages over developers, such as being able to quickly process data and provide fast responses, there are still many areas where human input is valuable or even essential. Developers bring invaluable experience and knowledge when it comes to understanding user needs and building applications based on said needs. Even if ChatGPT performs tasks faster than developers in certain cases, the complexity of coding software requires an understanding of the problem domain that only humans can provide.<br>The idea behind ChatGPT is that it can take a natural language request from a user and then generate a response in real-time without the need for manual coding or development. It’s an exciting concept but one that could pose some interesting challenges if implemented widely. For instance, how would ChatGPT handle complex tasks? How would it integrate with existing systems? Would its output be reliable and secure enough for production use?<br>These are questions that have yet to be answered, but it’s clear that this AI tool has the potential to change the way developers work but not to completely replace them.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-76\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-9.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“ChatGPT Lacks Creative Problem-Solving Skills” – Luke Fitzpatrick, CEO at Drsono</strong>.<br><br>“ChatGPT is an AI that automates writing code and has the potential to replace developers. However, there are some drawbacks to this technology that need to be considered. While ChatGPT may be able to process large chunks of code faster than a human, it lacks the creative problem-solving skills that developers bring to the table.<br>Developers often use their expertise to think outside the box and devise innovative new solutions to complex coding issues, something ChatGPT cannot do. The truth is ChatGPT could possibly supplement and complement skilled developers but ultimately cannot replace them entirely.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-77\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-10.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“Developers Still Needed for Quality Checking” – William Hogsett, CEO at Seota Digital Marketing.</strong><br><br>“I don’t believe that ChatGPT will replace developers completely. With the rate AI is being developed, it could possibly take over some tasks in the near future, but not all. Firstly, though it will likely be able to generate higher-quality code in the future, it will still need developers to examine and quality-check the data it provides.<br>Additionally, as it’s a language generator, it’s not able to be truly innovative or creative – two very important skills for developers. Finally, even if it someday learns to do everything a developer can, ChatGPT itself will still need developers to maintain and update it.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-78\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-11.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“No Tech is Proven to Replace Creativity” – Jake Albion, Owner of Albion Digital Web Studio.</strong><br><br>“No. It will make them more effective, like many other tools used to code, including GitHub Copilot or Emmet, and research solutions faster. You’ll still need to be able to understand how everything works.<br>Developers can focus on complex problems and reduce repetitive tasks, especially on platforms like WordPress. It may also widen the disparity of developers vs non-coders, but that won’t be for a while until it becomes more reliable for people who don’t want to code and hack shortcuts for their websites. Ultimately that means that people who understand how to conceptualize, plan, and develop software and websites (experts) will become more valuable and be able to charge more for their time.<br>The spectrum of how we work is widening, creating more opportunities, not less, mainly because no technology has proven to replace creativity and problem-solving.”</td></tr><tr><td><img class=\"wp-image-79\" style=\"width: 150px;\" src=\"https://sharing.knowledge/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/image-12.png\" alt=\"\"></td><td><strong>“AI Won’t Steal Your Job; Person Using AI Will” – Marcin Gwizdala, Chief Technical Officer at Tidio.</strong><br><br>“ChatGPT or AI in general will not replace developers. The person who uses AI will. In my opinion, this is the only valid response when it comes to the fear of AI stealing one’s job. The tool itself simply cannot do it. However, those developers that take advantage of emerging technologies adapt fast and learn to be proficient users of them have every chance to grow in their career much faster than the rest.<br>The modern tech environment does not tolerate stagnation. One can be sure that if they are not willing to grow, they will be replaced by someone possibly less experienced, but advanced with AI tools. We have to adapt to these conditions, whether we like it or not.”</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<!-- /wp:table -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Is ChatGPT going to replace programmers?</strong> — Well, <strong>surely not</strong>, according to these seven experts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tools such as ChatGPT can speed up the development process and reduce mundane tasks for developers. This will allow the professionals to spend more time on creative solutions and problem-solving. Professionals can elevate their efficiency and capabilities by synergizing with such tools.</p>\n